    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2868814561" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2868814561" />
    <a title="Jovana Autumn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41176805-jovana-autumn"><img alt="Jovana Autumn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618543441p2/41176805.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2868814561?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jovana Autumn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jovana Autumn" href="/user/show/41176805-jovana-autumn">Jovana Autumn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=classics-read">classics-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=books-i-own">books-i-own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=horror-and-dark-fiction">horror-and-dark-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=reviews">reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=2021">2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=read-in-serbian">read-in-serbian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=surprisingly-good">surprisingly-good</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41176805-jovana-autumn?shelf=gothic">gothic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2868814561" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer210150407522084374"><blockquote>
  <i>
    <b>&quot;Ambrosio was yet to learn, that to a heart unacquainted with her, Vice is ever most dangerous when lurking behind the Mask of Virtue.” </b>
  </i>
</blockquote><br/><br/>How did Matthew G. Lewis write a scandalous, dreadful, and comical novel of the gothic genre? <br/><br/>There are a few things to keep in mind before reading The Monk. <br/><br/>1) <b>The novel form was still young</b>; it did exist before but was <u>not</u> highly respected. It was thought of as a lesser value literature work, and men would often be embarrassed to read them or admit</span>
  <span id="freeText210150407522084374" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>
    <b>"Ambrosio was yet to learn, that to a heart unacquainted with her, Vice is ever most dangerous when lurking behind the Mask of Virtue.” </b>
  </i>
</blockquote><br /><br />How did Matthew G. Lewis write a scandalous, dreadful, and comical novel of the gothic genre? <br /><br />There are a few things to keep in mind before reading The Monk. <br /><br />1) <b>The novel form was still young</b>; it did exist before but was <u>not</u> highly respected. It was thought of as a lesser value literature work, and men would often be embarrassed to read them or admit in public that they had read them. <br /><br />In current times, the novel form is the most popular one, which goes to show how public opinion can, more often than not, be in the wrong. <br /><br />2) <b>Gothic novels, in particular, </b> were criticized because of their construction, they have caused alarm within the moralists and rationalists of the time. They seemingly had no finesse, simple characters that felt unrealistic(Either completely purist or devilish), and an unbelievable plot. <br /><br />The novel is most often set in a foreign country (like Italy or Spain), in a barbarous medieval past (anachronism can be an issue in writing), inhabited by virtuous heroes and chaste heroines and evil villains, often set in ancient castles and surrounded by ruins.<br />The typical Gothic novel can feel repetitive in the sense that a thousand versions have been spawned from a limited set of elements. <br /><br />Furthermore, analyzing the early Gothic novels of Romanticism proves to be dull and unrewarding work. Contemporary criticism of the gothic has concentrated on the tendency of the gothic to write in terms of surfaces—its speciality is its superficiality. <br /><br /><u>In other words, deeper digging won't provide the reader with satisfying results with this genre.</u> <br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Lewis's Monk is an exception from the rule.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />3) Matthew G. Lewis took a lot of inspiration for his novel from the work of German writers of the movements <b>Sturm-und-Drang</b>(Storm and stress, they put a lot of accent on revolt, strong feelings, and the cult of the genius) and <b>Schauer-Romantik</b>(in contrast to the works of other English Gothic writers, the German writers were far more graphic in portraying horror: ghosts, murders, rapes, secret societies, devils, and tortures). <br /><br />Concrete instances where Lewis mentions this connection with the German influence is finding the legend of the Bleeding Nun in German folklore, introducing the character of the Wandering Jew, Schiller's work like "Der Geisterseher" gave him the idea of a picture of the Madonna being used to inspire love for a living woman.<br /><br />English literature couldn't have provided Lewis with the horror elements written in his novel. The works that he could have read with the most horrid elements were Milton's Paradise Lost, Jacobean Tragedies, and lyrical forms from the" graveyard school", none of which come close to <i>The Monk</i> in terms of horror evocation. <br /><br />There is a passage from an essay published in 1826 "On the Supernatural in Poetry" by one of the most beloved writers of the English Gothic novel — Ann Radcliffe, which portrays the key difference between the female and male Gothic. Radcliffe writes: <blockquote>
  <i>"<b>terror</b> ‘expands the soul, and awakens the faculties to a high degree of life’, <b>horror</b> ‘contracts, freezes, and nearly annihilates them." </i>
</blockquote><br /><br />While Radcliffe accentuates the aesthetic, constant suspense and mystery, fear and anticipation Lewis does the opposite with his short episodic chapters and short climaxes. <br />The first type requires a certain type of reader - a curious explorer, one who can self-insert in the shoes of the hero/heroine — What the heroes fear, and often faint before is what the reader also encounters, enduring all the agonies of suspense. <br /><br /><u>Unsurpisingly, a lot of readers didn't have the time to self-insert in a work that in the long run provided zero didactic benefits and a plot so distant from their everyday life with characters being a flat representation of what is considered good and bad.</u><br /><br />This is where the brilliant wit of <i>The Monk</i> comes in. <br /><br /><i>The Monk</i> is a novel of mainly two things - a novel of bad faith and a novel that parodies gothic novels. <br /><br /><u>Bad faith is referring to the religious milieu of the time, a critic of the Catholic church and the religious order in it.</u><br />The Church of Rome was supposed to prey upon the fear and irrationality of its devotees, it was supposed to thrive on idolatry, and its spirituality was thus debased and materialistic. <br />That is why Ambrosio's first fall into temptation was after seeing the statue of Madonna, said to be modeled by the face of Matilda, and through Matilda, the devil used art and the visual(like the mirror which shows an image of the nearly naked Antonia)to lure Ambrosio into sin. <br /><br />Ambrosio's sexuality is of an almost intellectual kind, he knows that purity comes with modesty, and the real turn-on for him is precisely that modesty excludes sex.<br />Or in layman's terms, purity attracts him because it is devoid of sex. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Ambrosio is satiated and disgusted by Matilda after they have entered their relationship. He pulls away from her to Antonia, for whom he feels the same disgust after he raped her. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Ambrosio, along with Agnes, is in fact, a victim of his church order and the oppression(celibacy - for which the Protestant Church was against) and superficial values that stood behind it(idolization and indulgence). <br /><br />Another aspect where Lewis differs from the traditional Gothic novel is <u>the deliberate eroticization of modesty</u> and <u>the portrayal of characters as neither entirely good nor entirely bad</u>. <br /><br />Both of these can apply to Agnes and <br />Virginia de Villa-Franca. <br />Agnes is a heroine of good heart and virtues<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ but she did break her celibacy and engaged in a sexual act as a nun. She is never villanized because of that, as she never wished anything but to marry the man she loved and didn’t feel the call of God nor the wish to be a nun.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> Her sin, in comparison with the sin of her domina, is of lesser value. <br /><br />A more subtle example of differentiation from the sentimental and gothic trope of an innocent fair maiden is supposedly the virginal, virtuous, Virginia.<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ She displays self-consciousness — she makes sure that she is seen nursing the unfortunate Agnes; she is aware of the attraction of female demureness and modesty and displays it to Lorenzo. She is determined to be seen as pure and compassionate in his company because she knows that there is a prospect of a union between the two.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Whether it's the clear parody of Genesis <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[when the serpent bites Ambrosio, <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> or a more carefully hidden one as in the character of Virginia de Villa-Franca or an inserted monologue where he anticipates the reaction of the future critic— nobody can deny that Matthew G. Lewis wrote an entertaining piece of fiction with an overall humorous tone.<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>"An author, whether good or bad, or between both, is an animal whom every body is privileged to attack: for though all are not able to write books, all conceive themselves able to judge them.” </i>
</blockquote><br /><br />I can only imagine the journey of 19-year-old Lewis while writing this novel.<br /><br />With its episodic structure, and the insertion of poetry this novel is truly one of the romantic movement marked by the merge of literary forms. Lewis filled the book with ballads, legends, and folktales that intertwined with the two main stories: Ambrosio's sin and the love story of Agnes and Raymond. <br /><br />However, there are some technical mistakes like confusing the titles of the religious order, misquoting in epigrams, and almost poor narration at certain chapters that prevented me from fully enjoying the novel. <br /><br />I consider a novel a success if it makes me think and <i>The Monk</i> certainly did provide me with thinking material. <br />That proves a gothic novel of the 18th century can indeed be both fun and horrid; surely, worth reading if one is interested in romanticism and its gothic genre. <br /><br /><b>P. S. A note for future readers</b>, The Oxford world's classics edition of this book has a stellar introduction and footnotes that provide a good deal of information(it helped me a lot in both understanding the book and writing a review about it) — I highly recommend it. <br />--------------------------------------------------------------------------<br />Okay, this turned out to be a lot more interesting than I thought. Review to come.</span>
  <a data-text-id="210150407522084374" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


